		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">For example Testis is 32 KB PRG and only 16 KB CHR</div><br /><img src="http://pics.pineight.com/lj/orly.png" alt="Image" /><br />Which of the seven Tetris pieces looks most like a <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/testis#English" class="postlink">gonad</a>? <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'm not sure if there is a difference between /CE and /OE. On RAMs of course there is a difference (when writing to it you want /CE low but /OE high).</div>
<br />In 6264 datasheets I've seen, /WE overrides /OE, so that it'll still work even if you tie /OE to /CE. The datasheets mention supporting both "8080 style buses" that use /RD and /WR and "6502 style buses" that use /CE and R/W.

		

